			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Clerics???<a name="28497"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 17 04 9:45 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I actually switched from a shaman to my bard.  Started out as a 'spur of the moment' thing to level up my 2nd ever created character.  He'd been sitting inactive on my account for around 4 years<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />  Anyway, to cut the story short, you're missing a couple of details in this with regards to the shaman perspective.
<br />

<br />
Currently, the healing ratios are: (this has been confirmed as the 'healing ratio' by SoE representatives)
<br />
Cleric 100%
<br />
Druid 68% (with respect to cleric)
<br />
Shaman 47% (with respect to cleric)
<br />

<br />
I am less familiar with the druid argument, and personally (&lt;- shaman bias still) I don't feel they have as much need for improvement. However, most shaman are asking less to encroach on the cleric realm, as they are asking to get closer to druids healing capability.
<br />
The problem for shamans is that they are being penalised for having a slow capability. However, with the introduction of slow mitigation and immunity, and, especially in higher-end PoP and most of GoD, mobs have huge DPS, but low hps, making for short fights. In these fights, you need fast powerful healing capability.  Clerics have this, and druids to a lesser degree. Shaman, have a 300/tick (360ish if you have the GoD spell) HoT, and a mana inefficient 1300 base direct heal casting in 3.8 seconds. With AA's and focus, this reaches around 1700 direct, with 3100ish crit heals. Don't even mention that piece of crap called a 'percentage CH' shaman get - 10 second cast to heal max of 1950 is so worthless on anything past tier 1 as to be insulting. On mobs that hit 1300+, and can triple or quad, even with a tanks' mitigation, a shaman cannot hope to ever heal a main tank, and is relegated to spot heals on MT, or 'trying' to heal the cleric if they get agro. 
<br />
In a game that is supposed to allow a bit of diversity in healers, GoD especially is making a cleric or two (or cleric and druid) a 'must have', and the extremely short fight times (with slow immunity or mitigation) is marginalising the slow capability of shaman.  So Shaman are understandably upset with the state they're in, where they are fairly useless healers, people prefer a beastlord for slowing, (h*ll, since playing my bard *I* prefer a beastlord for slowing) and they are not equipped spell wise for burst damage, where a druid at least has some decent nukes.
<br />
Sure, shaman can heal well enough in BoT, or tactics etc, and well equipped ones with well equipped tanks can do EP's, but in GoD, they are repeatably being passed over for groups, and asked for 'buffs please' by guildmates before they enter a trial.
<br />
Not to mention that fact that shaman spells have increasingly become more and more mana inefficient to make up for the ability to canabalise, they cannot do anything for a reasonable period of time without having to constantly canni. In GoD, pausing to canni is a luxury you sometimes just don't have.
<br />

<br />
Shaman recently received an improved heal, 1550 or so if memory serves me correctly, but even that is a stop gap, and doesn't really address the real problem; shaman are designed for extended fights, and the trend these days for short, high damage fights is simply making them less and less needed.
<br />

<br />
I hope that helps to somewhat explain the shaman perspective.  </span></td>
			</tr><tr>
