			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Clerics???<a name="28686"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 18 04 1:49 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Shammy brings: best slow in the game, backup heals, strong DOTs, buffs, avatar, haste
<br />

<br />
Enchanter brings: slow albeit not as good, better haste, KEI, mez/charm
<br />

<br />

<br />
Shammy wins. Bard covers the mez. Chanter haste is superior but not so much so as to make up for the total inability to heal. </span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
For me, chanter wins.  Shammy spot heals are irrelevant 99% of the time if the main healer is paying attention.  Bard can cover mez sure, but a chanter typically can do it better, freeing you up to do other things.  Need I mention the gutwreching DPS a chanter can add to a group by charming?
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Shammy vs. BST: Comes down to DPS vs. heals. This depends on the rest of the group I suppose. My regular group never has any issues with DPS, so we always prefer the shammy.
<br />

<br />
Also, don't lose sight of the value of those shaman buffs. Focus + Boar + Wrulan + FA make a big difference. Maybe you don't need them if you're in Time gear. Not being in Time gear myself, I couldn't say. For me, they make a big difference. </span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
More DPS is always good.  It always stacks.  Beastlords also buff about as well as shamans, and Ferocity is better than FA.  Shamans can buff AGI higher than BST, but AGI's value is widely debated and Wrulan widely regarded as a waste of a buff slot.  A Beastlord can cap most melees stats, or close enough, even in Bazaar gear.  Paragon is extremely nice.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">In hard LDONs or GOD trials, I think an &quot;almost as good&quot; slow is not adequate. IMO, every 1% more the mob is slowed makes a big honkin difference when the mob hits in the 1K range.</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Let's look at 50% mitigated slows on a mob that triples for 1k with an unslowed delay of 20 (hitting every 2 seconds).  I don't know what GoD trial mobs hit for, as I have yet to buy Gates, so let me know if this would be a poor example.
<br />

<br />
Shaman = 37.5% slowed.  Mob delay 32 hitting every 3.2 seconds.
<br />
Enchanter = 35% slowed.  Mob delay 31 hitting every 3.1 seconds
<br />
Beastlord = 32.5% slowed, mob delay 30 hitting every 3.0 seconds.
<br />

<br />
Or, if you prefer DPS numbers, this mob is 1500DPS as a baseline...
<br />

<br />
Shaman slowed: 937 DPS
<br />
Enchanter slowed: 975DPS
<br />
Beastlord slowed: 1012DPS
<br />

<br />
On lesser damaging mobs the gap is much smaller, BSTs generally can get a mob slowed faster than shaman as well, so the overall damage output for the mob over the course of the fight will be very similar, especially for shorter fights (which is the trend these days).  The more the tank mitigates a mob's damamge output, the less of a gap there is as well.  But shamans get Malo(s) and Beastlords don't, you say?  How much does that matter in your group with a bard?  How about the 5sec cast time on Malos?  More time a totally unslowed mob is pounding your MT.  Is the beastlord able to offset that 75 point difference in mob DPS by increasing the DPS of the group significantly more than a shaman can(remember Ferocity is more attack than FA, not to mention the beastlord's own DPS)?  Probably.  Shaman can add DPS with DOTs, you say?  Disease DOTs take so long to do anything that they're only useful for soloing, poison DOTs generate so much aggro that you have to wait a good while before casting them, and using more than one almost guarantees you're tanking the rest of the fight (shamans are not necros, they can't FD off their poison counter aggro).  But shamans can nuke... yes, the worst of any priest or caster class.
<br />

<br />
Sure, there are some group compositions that benefit greatly from a shaman.  There are many many more where a shaman adds little or nothing.  The healing upgrades are a bandaid, it's the game design philosophy that's outdating the class.  The more the game drifts towards high DPS short fights, the less a shaman has a place in it.  It's good for a class to replaceable.  It's not good if another class is typically a better choice.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%"><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=776546" target="_blank">Waeland Mistnote</a></br>
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=294811" target="_blank">Harwel Spiritwalker</a>
</span></td>
