				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Clerics???<a name="28705"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 18 04 2:32 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Shammy spot heals are irrelevant 99% of the time if the main healer is paying attention. </span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Shaman slowed: 937 DPS 
<br />
Enchanter slowed: 975DPS 
<br />
Beastlord slowed: 1012DPS </span></blockquote> 
<br />

<br />
In my experience, group with a shammy has considerably less downtime than group without a shammy.  Neither group tends to die disproportionately--i.e., neither group has issues with the heals being adequate per se.  But the shammy free group needs med breaks where the shammy having group does not.
<br />

<br />
I attribute this to two things:
<br />

<br />
1st, those irrelevant spot heals reducing the burden on the primary healer's mana.
<br />
2nd, the difference in slow effectiveness.
<br />

<br />
Neither an enchanter nor a beastlord can provide those spot heals or a slow of equal capacity.  
<br />

<br />
Additionally, I am unconvinced by the argument that shammy DPS sucks.  Maybe it's because I'm in the same room with our shammy, but we have a regular drill established under which she VPs an add and starts dotting it early.  She gets a lot of value out of those dots.
<br />

<br />
Also, as an aside, the same argument you make about why Malo is a bad factor to consider -- delay during which you have an unslowed mob -- also cuts against an enchanter's slow utility.  I have watched enchanters who try to slow in hard LDONs or GOD trials without tashing first.  With shocking regularity, the pattern is: slow bounces and chanter dies before anyone even knows what hit him.  Robes crumple like tin foil.  So they tash first, then wait a sec, then slow.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Bard can cover mez sure, but a chanter typically can do it better, freeing you up to do other things. Need I mention the gutwreching DPS a chanter can add to a group by charming? </span></blockquote> 
<br />

<br />
On a two pull, how is the enchanter's mez better?  It costs me one song and about 1 second's dps every 3 ticks to keep an add iced.  That's not enough loss of my utility to justify giving up the shammy's spot heals and superior slows.  Also, arguments about a beastlord's buffs don't matter when the comparison is an enchanter -- so we also give up shammy buffs to save me that one song + 1 second's DPS.
<br />

<br />
In hard LDON or GOD instanced zones, I refrain from bringing 3 or more pulls.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">There are many many more where a shaman adds little or nothing. </span></blockquote> 
<br />

<br />
I think this is the key spot where we part ways.  Maybe you spend a lot of time in groups where the shammy really does add little or nothing.  I generally don't find myself in perfect or even well-balanced groups.  I find myself in groups of whichever friends happen to be online.  As I say, I absolutely despise having to go fishing for a specific class to fill out a group.  
<br />

<br />
So, for me, the overall versatility of the shaman is indispensable.</span></td>
