				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Clerics???<a name="28708"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 18 04 2:36 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>   As I see it, the difficulty with Clerics isn't that they are the best healers, but that they have too many supplemental abilities which are irreplaceable.
<br />

<br />
   For example, let's say your only Wisdom caster is a Shaman.  While Shaman get a variety of good buffs, the major buff (hp/ac) is the province of the Cleric.  Nothing a Shaman does can match a Cleric's performance in this area.  But why not give the Shaman a buff that- while not as good as Virtue- is reasonably close, and doesn't stack with Virtue?  This means that if you're in a group with only a Shaman, you'd have more hit points than if you were in a group with only a Cleric.  But you'd have even more if you were with both.
<br />

<br />
   Or consider Divine Arbitration.  Let's imagine we give this ability to Monks.  Now, Monks would never get a group invite because they were going to be the main healer.  Equalizing life totals is great- but somewhat pointless when you don't have any group heals to back it up.  But put a Monk in the same group with a Paladin, and suddenly a Druid healer doesn't look that bad.  The Monk can cover the emergencies Arbitration is useful for, the Paladin can group heal to recover from the Arbitration, and the Druid can function as the main healer.
<br />

<br />
   How about percent runes?  We could give Enchanters a better, non-stackable, percent rune than Clerics receive, and replace the unuseably bad Nillipus/Song of Shields with percent runes for Bards.  So if you just had a Cleric, you'd be pretty well off.  But if you had Enchanter + Druid or Bard + Druid, you'd have solid mitigation to help out your weaker healing.
<br />

<br />
   Or how about adding 'Healing Focus, Complete Heal excluded' to songs like Rizlona's and Call of the Muse?  Such an effect wouldn't be particularly helpful for Clerics (who tend to outheal damage anyway), but it would be an enormous equalizer for Shaman/Druids.
<br />

<br />
   Essentially, you give non-healing classes abilities that can bolster the Shaman/Druid sufficiently that they can operate as main healer in high level content, but designed so that they only minimally bolster a Cleric.  The Cleric would still be the better healer and a more convienient group slot.  But if you picked the right mixture of other classes, you'd be able to get away with a 'lesser' healer, because they'd have the right abilities to cover the gaps.
<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"></span></td>
			</tr><tr>
