			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Clerics???<a name="28740"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 18 04 4:09 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Additionally, I am unconvinced by the argument that shammy DPS sucks. Maybe it's because I'm in the same room with our shammy, but we have a regular drill established under which she VPs an add and starts dotting it early. She gets a lot of value out of those dots. </span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Parse those dots and see what they're actually doing.  Those dots also stand a good chance of breaking root unless the shaman is using all dots with no initial DD.  Additionally, if the mobs summons this isn't a very wise strategy.  How does your tank find pulling the mobs off the shaman afterwards?
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">With shocking regularity, the pattern is: slow bounces and chanter dies before anyone even knows what hit him. Robes crumple like tin foil. So they tash first, then wait a sec, then slow. </span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
This is more a function of gear than class in today's EQ.  The gap between haves and have-nots is large and copious amounts of hit points are on everything at the higher end.  My friend's chanter is in a guild that farms VT and is 1 kill from EPs.  Far from uber gear but... my shaman is a Bazaar Wonder as I am in a friends-and-family guild that raids stuff like Chardok and CoM.   The chanter has notably more HP than my shaman, and with runes is far better at taking a pounding.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">On a two pull, how is the enchanter's mez better? It costs me one song and about 1 second's dps every 3 ticks to keep an add iced. That's not enough loss of my utility to justify giving up the shammy's spot heals and superior slows.</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Bard has to re-mez more often.  Are you never resisted on a re-mez?  I don't have ancient mez myself, and probably never will.  I wouldn't be so quick to discount the value of whatever song you're dropping, either.  And again, the difference in shaman and chanter slows is not generally noticeable.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Also, arguments about a beastlord's buffs don't matter when the comparison is an enchanter -- so we also give up shammy buffs to save me that one song + 1 second's DPS. </span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Shaman buffs are readily available in PoK, are you so willing to give up only FA to forego a chanter's charmed mob DPS, superior CC, and superior haste?
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">I think this is the key spot where we part ways. Maybe you spend a lot of time in groups where the shammy really does add little or nothing. I generally don't find myself in perfect or even well-balanced groups. I find myself in groups of whichever friends happen to be online. As I say, I absolutely despise having to go fishing for a specific class to fill out a group. </span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
I think you're probably right.  You see, I generally play with my friends also.  It so happens that the group consists of a 2box warrior-wizard, a ranger, a chanter, a cleric, and (til recently) my shaman.  I found I was able to contribute much more as a bard.  But even still: when that group isn't available, my GF and I log on my bard and her ranger, we grab a plate tank of any type, a cleric or druid, and 2 dps, and we go.  If we need heavier slows than requiem of time, BST and ENC can provide it, and a ton more DPS than a shaman.  After 120 days /played on my shaman, they don't usually even make my list unless it's an /lfg friend or guildy.  Sad but true.
<br />

<br />
</span></td>
