		</table></td><td class="PanelBody" valign="Top"><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" border="0" width="100%">
			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Clerics???<a name="28748"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 18 04 4:33 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">This is more a function of gear than class in today's EQ. . . . The chanter has notably more HP than my shaman, and with runes is far better at taking a pounding. 
<br />
</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
True certainly, but IMO not a valid comparison.  Enchanters are silk classes, shammies are chain classes.  With equivalent gear, therefore, shammies should always be able to take more abuse than enchanters.
<br />

<br />
Agreed a VT-geared enchanter can take more damage than a bazaar shaman.  Run the test between a VT-geared enchanter and a VT-geared shaman though -- I suspect shammy will win.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Bard has to re-mez more often. Are you never resisted on a re-mez? I don't have ancient mez myself, and probably never will.</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Of course I'm resisted.  But Lullaby lasts longer than a regular bard buff.  Every once in a while I drop a second song for one cycle as I have to resing mez.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">I wouldn't be so quick to discount the value of whatever song you're dropping, either.</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
&quot;Whatever song&quot; almost invariably means Warsong of Zek.  So, on this hypothetical, the question really boils down to this:
<br />

<br />
Is the loss of Warsong of Zek for under half of the time the group spends meleeing (I generally don't pull triples, and can do my full twist once we finish the first mob and start on the second) more harmful to the group's overall success than the loss of a shaman's superior slow and spot heal capacity.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">And again, the difference in shaman and chanter slows is not generally noticeable</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
I'm not sure you meant the word &quot;noticeable&quot; literally, but I will nevertheless seize on it :P.  One may not notice the difference in the slows, but it's there and it's affecting the group's long-term efficiency.  As I say--groups without the shammy tend to run oom and need med breaks, while groups with the shammy just don't.
<br />

<br />
Maybe my experience is atypical.  
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Shaman buffs are readily available in PoK, are you so willing to give up only FA to forego a chanter's charmed mob DPS, superior CC, and superior haste? </span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
1.  Bought KEI lasts longer than bought Focus &amp; other buffs.  A bought KEI can easily last 2 adventures, 3 if we're fast.  Not so shammy buffs.  Not to mention blessing of replenishment and FA.
<br />

<br />
2.  Chanter charmed mob DPS is very very situational.  Maybe I have not grouped with the best charmers, but most of the chanters I group with tend to take the position that they WILL charm if we need it to win, but they prefer not to because the risk and chaos factor is so high.
<br />

<br />
3.  Superior CC is marginal as discussed above.
<br />

<br />
4.  Superior haste is also marginal.  Even if shammy never casts haste, most people I group with have either 36% or 41% haste items.  Isn't SLTW 60%?  So, at the abolutely maximum, superior chanter haste adds 4% haste.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">It so happens that the group consists of a 2box warrior-wizard, a ranger, a chanter, a cleric, and (til recently) my shaman. I found I was able to contribute much more as a bard. </span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Fair enough.  Nobody on this board is likely to argue that shaman &gt; bard :P.
<br />

<br />
I also accept the proposition that you don't want to boot either your enchanter friend or your ranger friend.  But wouldn't the group perform better in the long run if you did?  Query:
<br />

<br />
What happens when the cleric dies?  Unlucky heal agro, bad placement, whatever -- the cleric dies.  What do y'all do?  What we do is keep killing with the shammy on heals, then have the pally rez the cleric back in.  I see 0 backup heals in your standard configuration.
<br />

<br />
Wouldn't the group perform better if everyone had Focus, Boar, Wrulan, and Blessing of Replenishment running 24/7?  Wouldn't that ranger pump out more damage with FA?
<br />

<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">After 120 days /played on my shaman</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Meaning zero disrespect whatsoever, our group's shaman recently topped 320 days /played.  Our different assessments of the shaman's value may have something to do with play style.  I know ours is very adept at being a mana efficient spot healer, keeping everyone in the proper buffs, and putting out pretty d*mn respectable DPS.  I have no reason whatever to believe you didn't play your shaman quite well--maybe ours just plays exceptionally well, or integrates with our play style exceptionally well.  Who knows.
<br />
</span></td>
